# Calling the Banking API Server (PingOne Proxy Layer)

## Architecture Overview

```
Browser / UI
    │  (cookies only, no tokens)
    ▼
banking_api_server  ← BFF: holds all tokens server-side
    │
    ├─ /api/auth/*        → PingOne AS  (auth.pingone.{region}/{envId}/as/*)
    ├─ /api/auth/ciba/*   → PingOne CIBA (bc-authorize, token polling)
    └─ Internal services  → PingOne Management API (api.pingone.{region}/v1/*)
```

The UI **never** calls PingOne directly — it always calls the `banking_api_server` which proxies to PingOne. Tokens are stored in server-side sessions (`req.session.oauthTokens`), never in the response body.

---

## Config Access (Server-Side)

All PingOne config is read via `configStore.getEffective()` — **never hardcode URLs or credentials**:

```javascript
const configStore = require('../services/configStore');
const oauthConfig = require('../config/oauth'); // lazy getters backed by configStore

// Auth Server endpoints (lazy, config-driven)
oauthConfig.tokenEndpoint        // https://auth.pingone.{region}/{envId}/as/token
oauthConfig.authorizationEndpoint // .../authorize
oauthConfig.cibaEndpoint          // .../bc-authorize
oauthConfig.jwksEndpoint          // .../jwks
oauthConfig.userInfoEndpoint      // .../userinfo

// Client credentials
oauthConfig.clientId      // admin_client_id from configStore
oauthConfig.clientSecret  // admin_client_secret (decrypted in memory)
oauthConfig.scopes        // ['openid', 'profile', 'email']

// Raw config values
const envId  = configStore.getEffective('pingone_environment_id');
const region = configStore.getEffective('pingone_region') || 'com';

// URL builders
const authBase = `https://auth.pingone.${region}/${envId}/as`;
const apiBase  = `https://api.pingone.${region}/v1`;
```

